    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'SmartyPants Prenatal Formula', url: 'https://www.smartypantsvitamins.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 4, name: 'Nature Made Prenatal Multi + DHA Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Nature+Made+Prenatal+Gummies&tag=gummyguide-20' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 5, name: 'Olly Prenatal Gummies', url: 'https://www.olly.com/products/the-essential-prenatal' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 6, name: 'Ritual Essential Prenatal', url: 'https://ritual.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 7, name: 'Garden of Life mykind Organics Prenatal Gummies', url: 'https://www.gardenoflife.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 8, name: 'MegaFood Baby & Me 2 Prenatal Gummies', url: 'https://www.megafood.com/' },
  ],
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I start taking prenatal gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) recommends starting a prenatal supplement at least one month before you plan to conceive. Folate is critical during the first 28 days of pregnancy — often before you even know you are pregnant — because this is when the neural tube forms. If you are of reproductive age and could become pregnant, many healthcare providers suggest taking a prenatal vitamin as a standard precaution.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between folic acid and methylfolate?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Folic acid is the synthetic form of vitamin B9 used in most supplements and fortified foods. Your body must convert it into its active form (5-MTHF) through a multi-step enzymatic process. Methylfolate (5-MTHF) is the already-active form that your body can use immediately. An estimated 40% of the population carries an MTHFR gene variant that impairs the conversion of folic acid to its active form. For these individuals, methylfolate supplements may be more effective at maintaining adequate folate levels during pregnancy.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I get enough DHA from prenatal gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most prenatal gummies contain little to no DHA because omega-3 fatty acids are technically challenging to formulate in gummy form — they can cause fishy taste and texture issues. The recommended DHA intake during pregnancy is 200-300mg per day. Only a few prenatal gummies (such as One A Day at 200mg and Ritual at 350mg) approach this target. If your prenatal gummy contains less than 200mg DHA, consider adding a separate DHA supplement or consuming 2-3 servings of low-mercury fish per week.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why do most prenatal gummies not contain iron?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Iron is extremely difficult to include in gummy supplements for two reasons. First, iron has a strong metallic taste that is hard to mask with flavoring. Second, iron reacts with other ingredients in gummy formulations, causing discoloration and texture degradation. The recommended iron intake during pregnancy is 27mg per day. If your prenatal gummy does not contain iron, your healthcare provider may recommend a separate low-dose iron supplement, particularly in the second and third trimesters when iron demands increase significantly.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do I need a prenatal vitamin if I eat a healthy diet?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. Even with an excellent diet, it is difficult to consistently meet the increased nutrient demands of pregnancy through food alone. The body requires 50% more iron, significantly more folate, and additional DHA, iodine, and choline during pregnancy. ACOG recommends prenatal supplementation for all pregnant women regardless of dietary quality. A prenatal vitamin serves as nutritional insurance to fill potential gaps, not as a replacement for healthy eating.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the MTHFR gene variant and should I be concerned?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'MTHFR (methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase) is an enzyme that converts folic acid into its active form, methylfolate. Approximately 40% of the population carries one or two copies of a variant (C677T or A1298C) that reduces this enzyme activity by 30-70%. This means folic acid supplements may be less effective for these individuals. If you have a known MTHFR variant, or if you have not been tested and want to be cautious, choosing a prenatal with methylfolate instead of folic acid ensures your body receives folate in its bioavailable form.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are prenatal gummies as effective as prenatal pills?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Prenatal gummies and pills deliver the same active ingredients, but there are trade-offs. Gummies are easier to take (especially with morning sickness), have better compliance rates, and begin absorbing in the mouth. However, gummies generally contain fewer nutrients per serving because the gummy matrix limits how much can be included. Most prenatal gummies lack iron and have lower DHA levels compared to pills. If you choose gummies for tolerability, you may need to supplement iron and DHA separately.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I continue taking prenatal gummies while breastfeeding?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. ACOG and the American Academy of Pediatrics recommend continuing prenatal supplementation throughout breastfeeding. Your body continues to have elevated nutrient needs during lactation — particularly for DHA (which supports infant brain development through breast milk), choline, vitamin D, and iodine. Some women transition to a postnatal-specific supplement, but continuing your prenatal vitamin is an acceptable and commonly recommended approach.' },
    },
  ],
};
