    <section>
      <h2>Prenatal Nutrients: What the Science Says</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>Folate: Folic Acid vs. Methylfolate and the MTHFR Question</h3>
        <p>Folate is the single most critical nutrient in prenatal supplementation. The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends <strong>600mcg of folate daily during pregnancy to prevent neural tube defects</strong> — severe birth defects of the brain and spine that develop in the first 28 days of pregnancy, often before a woman knows she is pregnant. The CDC recommends all women of reproductive age consume at least 400mcg daily, increasing to 600-800mcg when trying to conceive or during pregnancy.</p>

        <p>The folic acid versus methylfolate debate centers on the <strong>MTHFR gene</strong>. Approximately 40% of the population carries at least one copy of the C677T or A1298C variant, which reduces the MTHFR enzyme activity by 30-70%. This enzyme is responsible for converting folic acid into its active form, 5-methyltetrahydrofolate (5-MTHF). For women with these variants, supplementing with methylfolate bypasses the impaired conversion step entirely, ensuring adequate folate delivery to the developing fetus.</p>

        <p>Should you get tested for MTHFR? Opinions vary. Some OB-GYNs recommend testing, while others argue that choosing methylfolate preemptively is simpler and eliminates the risk regardless. If you have a family history of neural tube defects or previous pregnancy complications, discuss MTHFR testing with your healthcare provider.</p>

        <table class="dose-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Folate Form</th><th>Conversion Required</th><th>Best For</th><th>Products on This List</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Folic Acid</td><td>Yes — requires MTHFR enzyme</td><td>Women without MTHFR variants</td><td>One A Day, Vitafusion, Nature Made, Olly</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Methylfolate (5-MTHF)</td><td>No — already active</td><td>MTHFR carriers, or anyone wanting certainty</td><td>SmartyPants, Ritual, MegaFood</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Organic Food Folate</td><td>Minimal — naturally in active form</td><td>Women prioritizing whole food sourcing</td><td>Garden of Life</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>DHA: Why Most Prenatal Gummies Fall Short</h3>

        <p><strong>Docosahexaenoic acid (DHA)</strong> is an omega-3 fatty acid that constitutes approximately 40% of the polyunsaturated fatty acids in the brain and 60% in the retina. During the third trimester, DHA accumulation in the fetal brain accelerates dramatically — the fetus accumulates approximately 67mg of DHA per day during this period. The World Health Organization and ACOG recommend at least 200mg of DHA daily during pregnancy.</p>

        <p>The problem: DHA is exceptionally difficult to formulate in gummies. Omega-3 oils are unstable, oxidize easily, and create a fishy taste and odor that undermines the gummy format's primary appeal. As a result, most prenatal gummies contain only 50-60mg of DHA — roughly 25-30% of the minimum recommendation. Only three products on our list deliver meaningful DHA doses: Ritual (350mg from microalgae), SmartyPants (288mg from fish oil), and One A Day (200mg).</p>

        <p>If your prenatal gummy contains less than 200mg of DHA, supplementing with a separate DHA product or consuming 2-3 servings per week of low-mercury fish (salmon, sardines, anchovies, herring) is strongly recommended.</p>

        <h3>Iron: The Nutrient Gummies Almost Never Include</h3>

        <p>During pregnancy, your blood volume increases by approximately 45%, demanding substantially more iron to produce hemoglobin. The recommended dietary allowance for iron during pregnancy is <strong>27mg per day</strong> — nearly double the 18mg recommended for non-pregnant women. Iron deficiency anemia affects up to 18% of pregnant women in the United States and is associated with preterm birth, low birth weight, and impaired infant cognitive development.</p>

        <p>Iron is the most frequently missing nutrient in prenatal gummies. The metallic taste is difficult to mask in a gummy, and iron reacts with other ingredients to cause discoloration and texture issues. Only two products on this list — One A Day and Olly — include iron. Ritual includes chelated iron, which is better tolerated but at a lower dose. If your prenatal gummy does not contain iron, <strong>speak with your healthcare provider about separate iron supplementation</strong>, particularly starting in the second trimester when iron demands peak.</p>
      </div>
