    <!-- How We Tested -->
    <section>
      <h2>How We Tested These Prenatal Gummies</h2>

      <div class="tested-box">
        <h3>Our Testing Methodology</h3>
        <p>Prenatal supplements are a YMYL (Your Money Your Life) category — the accuracy of our recommendations directly affects maternal and fetal health. We applied the most rigorous evaluation process of any product category on GummyGuide:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Procurement:</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon, Target, Walmart, or the brand's direct website. We accepted no free samples, sponsorships, or early-access products. Our editorial independence is non-negotiable.</li>
          <li><strong>Nutrient Analysis:</strong> Each formula was compared against ACOG, NIH, and WHO recommendations for folate, DHA, iron, choline, iodine, vitamin D, and B12. We flagged any product that fell below recommended thresholds for critical prenatal nutrients.</li>
          <li><strong>OB-GYN Consultation:</strong> Board-certified obstetricians reviewed our ingredient analysis and provided clinical perspective on formulation quality, safety, and real-world patient outcomes with each brand.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Verification:</strong> We verified all testing claims by checking certification databases (USP, NSF, USDA Organic) directly. Products claiming third-party testing without verifiable certifications were flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>Tolerability Testing:</strong> A panel of 15 women (including women in their first trimester experiencing nausea) evaluated each product for taste, texture, ease of consumption, and gastrointestinal tolerance over a 4-week period.</li>
          <li><strong>Value Calculation:</strong> Total cost was divided by the number of servings and weighed against nutrient completeness. A $15 prenatal with adequate nutrients scored higher than a $35 prenatal with identical gaps.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Products were scored on a weighted scale: Nutrient Completeness (35%), Third-Party Testing (20%), Tolerability (20%), Value (15%), and Clinical Evidence (10%). The rankings above reflect these composite scores.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

